{"type":"message","id":"7e68cbcc","parentId":"21e22437","timestamp":"2026-04-17T12:30:28.273Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! Port 3100 is listening on all interfaces (`*:3100`) but it's NOT associated with the openclaw-gateway process. The openclaw-gateway is on 18789. Port 3100 might be from a different service.\n\nLet me check what's on port 3100 and also understand the architecture better. I also see there's an `AAA` directory which is odd.\n\nAlso important: The openclaw-listener config says `gateway.url: ws://127.0.0.1:3102` but the gateway is actually on 18789. The listener has been trying to connect to the wrong port this whole time.\n \nSo there's a service bound to 0.0.0.0:3100 that's completely separate from the openclaw ecosystem. Port 3100 shows up in the listening ports but isn't tied to any openclaw processes—the gateway is on 18789 and the v8 services are on 3103 and 3105. This means the openclaw-listener has been pointing to the wrong gateway port all along.\n\nBut here's the puzzling part: the gateway is still functioning and accepting messages through the Control UI on 18789, and the hook system is working fine too, writing to ephemeral files. If the listener were truly broken and disconnected, how is any of this still working? The listener might not be critical for the webchat channel, or it could be handling a different function than I initially thought.\n\nLooking at what the listener actually does—it connects to the gateway via WebSocket, receives incoming messages, calls external APIs for intent and scoring, then processes and queues responses—none of that seems to be happening through the webchat path. The gateway directly handles webchat sessions and writes to ephemeral via hooks, so the listener might only be essential for specific channel integrations rather than the core message flow.\n\nThe real problems I need to address are the context-api crashes from the port conflict, the listener's misconfigured gateway connection, the wiki-learn cron job failing with a 401 error, and the fact that ephemeral-to-entity promotion isn't working as intended. For the deeper architecture questions, I'm realizing the v8 router on 3102 was a specific design choice in the 4.14 version that got replaced by direct hook-based patterns in the current setup, so I need to understand what the listener was actually doing in the old architecture before I can figure out what should run now.\n\nLooking at the ports more carefully, 3100 is listening on all interfaces but isn't being used by anything in the current config—the listener expects the gateway at 3102, which doesn't exist. This is a real gap: there's no local HTTP API for intent detection or general routing like the old system had. The gateway itself is only on 18789, and the v8 services are fragmented across 3103 and 3105. Let me look at what the Python scene-classifier is actually doing on 3105 to understand the full picture.","thinkingSignature":"2ffdf0b5b3385b14f9b85827b07ae18deb83c5e23e4c288519ef57e69ac83ebd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0zgm55h300ek_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 深入：检查3105 Python服务的配置和状态\ncat /home/ai/.openclaw/v8/scene-classifier/config/rule_overrides.json 2>/dev/null\necho \"---\"\n# 检查 scene-classifier 实际监听端口\ngrep -r \"port\\|listen\" /home/ai/.openclaw/v8/scene-classifier/api_server.py 2>/dev/null | head -10\necho \"---\"\n# 查看3105实际返回内容\ncurl -s http://localhost:3105/ 2>&1 | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":50851,"output":744,"cacheRead":21638,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73233,"cost":{"input":0.0152553,"output":0.0008927999999999999,"cacheRead":0.00129828,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.017446379999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776429006336,"responseId":"06315acdb45a8be96012bf2356c49f67"}}
