{"type":"message","id":"0f133a85","parentId":"19751d1d","timestamp":"2026-04-17T16:51:15.572Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-04-18 00:51 GMT+8] 深度思考"}],"timestamp":1776444675498}}
{"type":"message","id":"02f05711","parentId":"0f133a85","timestamp":"2026-04-17T16:52:01.331Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to deeply think about how to integrate with the existing framework. They've been patient through many rounds of analysis and want a creative solution that works within the actual architecture constraints.\n\nLet me think from first principles again.\n\n**The Core Problem:**\nHow to get an Agent to autonomously call `sessions_spawn` when a high-score task arrives.\n\n**What Actually Exists:**\n1. `auto-score-classify` hook fires on every message, calls 3103/3105, writes to ephemeral\n2. Ephemeral files are written but never read back by any automatic process\n3. HEARTBEAT.md is read on every heartbeat\n\n\n4. `sessions_spawn` is a tool available to the Agent\n5. SOUL.md is loaded at session start, not on every message\n\n**Key Insight:**\nThe Agent doesn't read ephemeral automatically. But what if the ephemeral file itself contained a trigger that the Agent would naturally respond to? If the ephemeral entry was written in a format that resembled a user message or command, and the Agent's SOUL.md had a rule to check for recent ephemeral entries, then on the next heartbeat or interaction, the Agent could discover and act on the high-score task without any special gateway modification.\n\n**The Missing Piece:**\nThere's no mechanism right now that reads ephemeral and makes the Agent aware of it.\n\n**Creative Integration Idea:**\nWhat if the ephemeral file itself served as a signal? The hook could write a special formatted entry, and the Agent could check for it during idle time or heartbeats through rules in SOUL.md. But that raises the question: what triggers the Agent to check ephemeral in the first place? It's not automatic.\n\n**The Real Bottleneck:**\nI keep circling around the same problem—the Agent isn't checking anything unless something prompts it to. Heartbeats could be that prompt, but I'd need to modify how heartbeat responses work to include the file content. Alternatively, the Agent could have a SOUL.md rule that forces a check on every turn, but that adds overhead to every single message.\n\n**New Direction:**\nWhat if instead of trying to work around the architecture, I accept that HEARTBEAT.md is checked every 30 seconds? The hook could write a special directive to it, and the Agent's SOUL.md could have a rule to check for that directive and respond to it. But that only works if there's actually a heartbeat happening, and right now there's no active heartbeat exchange happening.\n\nThe more realistic approach is: write the directive to ephemeral during the hook execution, then have SOUL.md contain a rule that makes the Agent check ephemeral on every turn. But that's inefficient—checking ephemeral on every turn wastes resources.\n\nThe actual insight is that the Agent can only act on things it becomes aware of through its input. The hook modifies the input through `event.context.bodyForAgent`, and the SOUL.md rules get applied to the input. If SOUL.md had a rule saying \"check for directives in the input and follow them,\" then the hook could inject a directive into the input that the Agent would naturally discover and act on.\n\nThe real solution is to accept the \"say one more thing\" compromise: inject a directive telling the Agent to call `sessions_spawn` with specific parameters, then have SOUL.md tell the Agent to treat this directive as a command and execute it immediately without generating any other text, followed by outputting \"NO_REPLY\" to suppress the redundant response. This is actually implementable—the Agent would see the directive, execute it, and the tool call would produce the subagent, but the Agent's final text output would be suppressed.\n\nThe question becomes whether `NO_REPLY` actually suppresses the text in this context, and if not, whether returning just the tool result would work instead.\n\nActually, the more practical path forward is to test the current system's constraints directly—check if `sessions_spawn` actually works as a tool, whether the Agent can parse directives from the input context, and what \"NO_REPLY\" actually does in this framework. Rather than continuing to theorize about mechanisms, I should run a live test to see what the system actually supports.","thinkingSignature":"145559bf6173bcb89560790df984ebd5c67dd8b7d122fc321ea78afe949e2ec5"},{"type":"text","text":"## 最终融合路径\n\n经过彻底推演，答案已经清晰：\n\n---\n\n### 真正的问题是什么\n\n不是\"如何让 Agent 自主调用\"，而是：\n\n> **Agent 的 bootstrap 文件（SOUL.md）只在 session 启动时加载一次。后续消息到达时，Agent 的输入只有用户消息，没有任何机制能让 Agent 主动检查外部状态。**\n\n这是框架设计层面的约束，不是代码问题。\n\n---\n\n### 唯一可融合的路径\n\n**把 hook 注入变成 Agent 的\"输入本身\"**。\n\n`event.context.bodyForAgent` 是发给 Agent 的最终文本。如果在 SOUL.md 里加一条规则：\n\n```\n当输入包含 [AUTO_ROUTE] 标记时，立即执行 sessions_spawn 工具调用，\n不要生成任何文字回复，执行完毕后输出 NO_REPLY。\n```\n\n那么 hook 注入时就变成：\n\n```\n[AUTO_ROUTE]\nsessions_spawn agentId=executor message=\"原始用户任务\"\n```\n\nAgent 收到后 → SOUL.md 规则触发 → 调用工具 → NO_REPLY。\n\n---\n\n### 为什么之前所有方案都失败了\n\n| 方案 | 失败原因 |\n|------|----------|\n| Agent 自检 context.json | 无检查触发时机 |\n| SOUL.md 规则动态生效 | SOUL.md 只在 session 启动时加载一次 |\n| hook 注入描述性指令 | Agent 不把描述变成工具调用 |\n| 修改消息为工具调用格式 | Agent 不解析 JSON，只生成文本 |\n\n所有方案的失败都是同一个根因：**假设 Agent 会在某个时间点主动检查外部状态**。但在 OpenClaw 的架构里，Agent 只有输入，没有轮询。\n\n---\n\n### 可行的最终方案\n\n**两条并行路径**：\n\n**路径 A（彻底解决）**：找到 Gateway 源码中 agent 调用的入口，在那里检查评分结果，有高评分直接走 spawn 路径，不启动主 agent。\n\n**路径 B（最小可用）**：hook 注入特殊格式指令 → SOUL.md 规则让 Agent 识别并执行 → 输出 NO_REPLY 抑制多余文字。\n\n路径 B 是当前唯一可实现的，但需要先验证：Agent 收到特殊格式指令后是否真的会调用工具而不生成文字。\n\n---\n\n### 我的建议\n\n**现在执行一次真实测试**，而不是继续纸上推演。发一条包含 `[AUTO_ROUTE]` 标记的消息给 Agent，看它的实际行为。这一个测试能结束整个讨论。"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":58,"output":1333,"cacheRead":140369,"cacheWrite":175,"totalTokens":141935,"cost":{"input":0.0000174,"output":0.0015995999999999999,"cacheRead":0.00842214,"cacheWrite":0.000065625,"total":0.010104765}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776444675648,"responseId":"063198035ab1c2924bfc9a0f2407ab16"}}
